<hl>
<seg id=1> Thailand welcomes the surrender of Chasempan. </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> Bangkok reporter Zhengtin Liu reported. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> Yesterday the Thailand government welcomed two important members Chasempan and Longshia's surrender to the Phnom Penh government. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> The Spokesman for the Foreign Department Gusa said to reporters at a news conference "these two peoples surrender is a very important event to bring peace to Cambodia and make the situation there calmer." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> Gusa repeated that Thailand would never support any Cambodian group who wants to use Thai help to overthrow any government. </seg>
<seg id=6> Once the Thai government finds any foreign forces using their territory for military activities they will be punished by law </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> He also said that Thailand signed an extradition agreement with the Hun Sen government in may of this year, so Thailand also can return any captured criminals to the Phnom Penh government. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> Additionally news from Phnom Penh said that Thai Foreign Minsiter Dr. Su Ling has already invited Cambodian Foreign Minister Nanhong Ho to pay a visit to Bangkok early next year. So they can talk about peace along the border, and what to do about tens of thousands of Cambodian refugees who are now in Thailand.  Also Thailand is thinking to resume assistance programs for advanced training for Cambodians. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> In the middle of this month, the Asian Security Committee Summit will be held in Hanoi.  This committee has been considering accepting Cambodia as the tenth member and already gave permission to the leader of the Committee to prepare for having a welcoming ceremony to officially welcome Cambodia's joining in Hanoi. </seg>
</p>
</DOC>
